rop","meanings":["English:  see  Calthorpe  ."]},{"name":"Coathup","meanings":["English: variant of   Calthorpe  ."]}]},{"name":"WILLIAM","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":18,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":49,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"WILLIAM DE CALTHORPE was born in 1241, in Hales, Norfolk, England as the son of ROGER DE CALTHORPE. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Celia Burnham. He died in 1306, in his hometown, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1241–1306":"1241–1306","1240–1269":"1240–1269","1265–Male":"1265–Surnud","1267–1321":"1267–1321","1269–1324":"1269–1324","1220–1241":"1220–1241","1259":"1259","1269":"1269","1324":"1324","Abt 1267":"umbes 1267","1267":"1267","1321":"1321","1265":"1265","122